# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: decline-in-insect-populations
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-1-dichloroethane] Large volumes of 1,1-dichloroethane are manufactured, with annual production exceeding 1 million pounds in the United States.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-1-dichloroethane] It is mainly used as a feedstock in chemical synthesis, chiefly of 1,1,1-trichloroethane.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-1-dichloroethane] It is also used as a solvent for plastics, oils and fats, as a degreaser, as a fumigant in insecticide sprays, in halon fire extinguishers, and in cementing of rubber.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-1-dichloroethane] It is used in manufacturing of high-vacuum resistant rubber and for extraction of temperature-sensitive substances.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-1-dichloroethane] Thermal cracking at 400–500 °C and 10 MPa yields vinyl chloride.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-1-dichloroethane] In the past, 1,1-dichloroethane was used as a surgical inhalational anesthetic.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-1-dichloroethane] In the atmosphere, 1,1-dichloroethane decomposes with half-life of 62 days, chiefly by reaction of photolytically produced hydroxyl radicals.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichlorobenzene] It is mainly used as a precursor chemical in the synthesis of agrochemicals, as a preferred solvent for dissolving and working with fullerenes, as an insecticide, and in softening and removing carbon-based contamination on metal surfaces.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichlorobenzene] The reaction also affords the 1,4- and small amounts of the 1,3-isomer.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichlorobenzene] The 1,4- isomer is preferred over the 1,2- isomer due to steric hindrance.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichlorobenzene] The 1,3- isomer is uncommon because it is a meta- compound, while chlorine, like all halogens, is an ortho/para- director in terms of electrophilic aromatic substitution.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichlorobenzene] It is mainly used as a precursor to 1,2-dichloro-4-nitrobenzene, an intermediate in the synthesis of agrochemicals.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichlorobenzene] In terms of niche applications, 1,2-dichlorobenzene is a versatile, high-boiling solvent.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichlorobenzene] It is a preferred solvent for dissolving and working with fullerenes.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichlorobenzene] It is an insecticide for termites and locust borers, historically used by the United States Forest Service to combat widespread bark beetle outbreaks.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichlorobenzene] 1,2-Dichlorobenzene is also used in softening and removing carbon-based contamination on metal surfaces.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichlorobenzene] Data from human exposure to 1,2-dichlorobenzene shows that concentrations of 100 ppm have been reported to cause sporadic irritation of the eyes and respiratory tract.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichlorobenzene] The Occupational Safety and Health Administration and the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health have set occupational exposure limits at a ceiling of 50 ppm, over an eight-hour workday.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] The chemical compound **1,2-dichloroethane**, commonly known as **ethylene dichloride** (**EDC**), is a chlorinated hydrocarbon.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] It is a colourless liquid with a chloroform-like odour.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] The most common use of 1,2-dichloroethane is in the production of vinyl chloride, which is used to make polyvinyl chloride (PVC) pipes, furniture and automobile upholstery, wall coverings, housewares, and automobile parts.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] 1,2-Dichloroethane is also used generally as an intermediate for other organic chemical compounds, and as a solvent.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] It forms azeotropes with many other solvents, including water (at a boiling point of 70.5 °C or 158.9 °F or 343.6 K) and other chlorocarbons.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] Although the *Gezelschap* in practice did not do much in-depth scientific research, they and their publications were highly regarded.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] Part of that acknowledgement is that 1,2-dichloroethane was called "Dutch oil" in old chemistry.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] This is also the origin of the archaic term "olefiant gas" (oil-making gas) for ethylene, for in this reaction it is ethylene that makes the Dutch oil.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] "Olefiant gas" is the etymological origin of the modern term "olefins", the family of hydrocarbons of which ethylene is the first member.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] Nearly 20 million tons of 1,2-dichloroethane are produced annually in the United States, Western Europe, and Japan.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] Approximately 95% of the world's production of 1,2-dichloroethane is used in the production of vinyl chloride monomer (VCM) with hydrogen chloride as a byproduct.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] VCM is the precursor to polyvinyl chloride.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] The hydrogen chloride can be re-used in the production of more 1,2-dichloroethane via the oxychlorination route described above.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] 1,2-Dichloroethane has been used as degreaser and paint remover but this use has phased out due to its toxicity.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] As a useful 'building block' reagent, it is used as an intermediate in the production of diverse organic compounds such as ethylenediamine and higher ethyleneamines.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] In the laboratory it is occasionally used as a source of chlorine, with elimination of ethene and chloride.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] Via several steps, 1,2-dichloroethane is a precursor to 1,1,1-trichloroethane.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] Historically, before leaded petrol was phased out, chloroethanes were used as an additive in petrol to prevent lead buildup in engines.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] It is also toxic (especially by inhalation due to its high vapour pressure) and possibly carcinogenic.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] Its high solubility and 50-year half-life in anoxic aquifers make it a perennial pollutant and health risk that is very expensive to treat conventionally, requiring a method of bioremediation.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] While the chemical is not used in consumer products manufactured in the U.S., a case was reported in 2009 of molded plastic consumer products (toys and holiday decorations) from China that released 1,2-dichloroethane into homes at levels high enough to produce cancer risk.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] Substitutes are recommended and will vary according to application.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] Dioxolane and toluene are possible substitutes as solvents.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-2-dichloroethane] Dichloroethane is unstable in the presence of aluminium and, when moist, with zinc and iron.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-4-dichlorobenzene] It is used as a disinfectant, pesticide, and deodorant, most familiarly in mothballs in which it is a replacement for the more traditional naphthalene because of naphthalene's greater flammability (though both chemicals have the same NFPA 704 rating).
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-4-dichlorobenzene] It is also used as a precursor in the production of the chemically and thermally resistant polymer poly(*p*-phenylene sulfide).
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-4-dichlorobenzene] The compound can be purified by fractional crystallization, taking advantage of its relatively high melting point of 53.5 °C; the isomeric dichlorobenzenes and chlorobenzene melt well below room temperature.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-4-dichlorobenzene] Nitration gives 1,4-dichloronitrobenzene, a precursor to commercial dyes and pigments.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-4-dichlorobenzene] The chloride sites on *p*-DCB can be substituted with hydroxylamine and sulfide groups.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-4-dichlorobenzene] 2% Paradichlorobenzene used as a ceruminolytic agent for the treatment of impacted earwax.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-4-dichlorobenzene] Recreational abuse of PDCB has been described, usually through use of urinal cakes.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-4-dichlorobenzene] The United States Department of Health and Human Services (DHHS) and the International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) have determined that *p*-DCB may reasonably be anticipated to be a carcinogen.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-4-dichlorobenzene] This has been indicated by animal studies, although a full-scale human study has not been done.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-4-dichlorobenzene] The United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) has set a target maximum contaminant level of 75 micrograms of *p*-DCB per liter of drinking water (75 μg/L), but publishes no information on the cancer risk.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-4-dichlorobenzene] *p*-DCB is also an EPA-registered pesticide.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-4-dichlorobenzene] The United States Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) has set a maximum level of 75 parts of *p*-DCB per million parts air in the workplace (75 ppm) for an 8-hour day, 40-hour workweek.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-4-dichlorobenzene] A mechanism for the carcinogenic effects of mothballs and some types of air fresheners containing *p*-DCB has been identified in roundworms.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/1-4-dichlorobenzene] Due to its carcinogenic nature, use of paradichlorobenzene in the European Union is forbidden as an air freshener (since 2005) and in mothballs (since 2008).
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] 2 Esdras forms a part of the canon of Scripture in the Ethiopian Orthodox Church (an Oriental Orthodoxy body), though it is reckoned among the apocrypha by Catholics and Protestants.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Within Eastern Orthodoxy it forms a part of the canon although its usage varies by different traditions.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] 2 Esdras was translated by Jerome as part of the Vulgate, though he placed it in an appendix.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] As with 1 Esdras, some confusion exists about the numbering of this book.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The Vulgate of Jerome includes only a single book of Ezra, but in the Clementine Vulgate, 1, 2, 3 and 4 Esdras are separate books.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Protestant writers, after the Geneva Bible, called 1 and 2 Esdras of the Vulgate Ezra and Nehemiah, respectively, and called 3 and 4 Esdras of the Vulgate 1 Esdras and 2 Esdras, respectively.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] These then became the common names for these books in English Bibles.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Medieval Latin manuscripts denoted it 4 Esdras, which to this day is the name used for chapters 3–14 in modern critical editions, which are typically in Latin, the language of its most complete exemplars.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] It appears in the Appendix to the Old Testament in the Slavonic Bible, where it is called 3 Esdras, and the Georgian Orthodox Bible numbers it 3 Ezra.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] This text is sometimes also known as Apocalypse of Ezra — chapters 3–14 known as the Jewish Apocalypse of Ezra or 4 Ezra; in modern critical editions, chapters 1–2 are named as 5 Ezra, and chapters 15–16 as 6 Ezra.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Bogaert speculates that the "fourth book of Ezra" referred to by Jerome most likely corresponds to modern 5 Ezra and 6 Ezra combined, and notes a number of Latin manuscripts where these chapters are together in an appendix.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The first two chapters of 2 Esdras are found only in the Latin version of the book, and are called 5 Ezra by scholars.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] They are considered by most scholars to be Christian in origin; they assert God's rejection of the Jews and describe a vision of the Son of God.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] These are generally considered to be late additions (possibly third century) to the work.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Chapters 3–14, or the great bulk of 2 Esdras, is a Jewish apocalypse, also sometimes known as 4 Ezra or the Jewish Apocalypse of Ezra.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The latter name should not be confused with a later work called the *Greek Apocalypse of Ezra*.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The Ethiopian Church considers 4 Ezra to be canonical, written during the Babylonian captivity, and calls it Izra Sutuel (ዕዝራ ሱቱኤል).
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] It was also often cited by the Fathers of the Church.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] In the Eastern Armenian tradition, it is called 3 Ezra.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] It was written in the late first century CE following the destruction of the Second Temple.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Among Greek Fathers of the Church, 4 Ezra is generally cited as Προφήτης Ἔσδρας *Prophetes Esdras* ("The Prophet Ezra") or Ἀποκάλυψις Ἔσδρα *Apokalupsis Esdra* ("Apocalypse of Ezra").
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Most scholars agree that 4 Ezra was composed in Hebrew, which was translated into Greek, and then to Latin, Armenian, Ethiopian, and Georgian, but the Hebrew and Greek editions have been lost.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Slightly differing Latin, Syriac, Arabic, Ethiopic, Georgian, and Armenian translations have survived in their entirety; the Greek version can be reconstructed, though without absolute certainty, from these different translations, while the Hebrew text remains more elusive.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The modern Slavonic version is translated from the Latin.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] 4 Ezra consists of seven visions of Ezra the scribe.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The first vision takes place as Ezra is still in Babylon.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] He asks God how Israel can be kept in misery if God is just.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The archangel Uriel is sent to answer the question, responding that God's ways cannot be understood by the human mind.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Soon, however, the end would come, and God's justice would be made manifest.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Similarly, in the second vision, Ezra asks why Israel was delivered up to the Babylonians, and is again told that man cannot understand this and that the end is near.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] In the third vision, Ezra asks why Israel does not possess the world.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Uriel responds that the current state is a period of transition.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Here follows a description of the fate of evil-doers and the righteous.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Ezra asks whether the righteous may intercede for the unrighteous on Judgment Day, but is told that "Judgment Day is final".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The next three visions are more symbolic in nature.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The fourth is of a woman mourning for her only son.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] She is transformed into a city when she hears of the desolation of Zion.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Uriel says that the woman is a symbol of Zion.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The fifth vision concerns an eagle with three heads and 20 wings (12 large wings and eight smaller wings "over against them").
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The eagle is rebuked by a lion and then burned.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The explanation of this vision is that the eagle refers to the fourth kingdom of the vision of Daniel, with the wings and heads as rulers.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The final scene is the triumph of the Messiah over the empire.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The sixth vision is of a man, representing the Messiah, who breathes fire on a crowd that is attacking him.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] This man then turns to another peaceful multitude, which accepts him.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Finally, a vision of the restoration of scripture is related.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] God appears to Ezra in a bush and commands him to restore the Law.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Ezra gathers five scribes and begins to dictate.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] After 40 days, he has produced 204 books, including 70 works to be published last.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The "seventy" might refer to the Septuagint, most of the apocrypha, or the lost books that are described in the Bible.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] But it is more probable that the number is just symbolic.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Almost all Latin editions of the text have a large lacuna of 70 verses between 7:35 and 7:36 that is missing because they trace their common origin to one early manuscript, *Codex Sangermanensis I*, from which an entire page had been cut out very early in its history.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] In 1875 Robert Lubbock Bensly published the lost verses and in 1895 M.R.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] James oversaw a critical edition from Bensly's notes restoring the lost verses from the complete text found in the *Codex Colbertinus*; this edition is used in the Stuttgart edition of the Vulgate.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] For more information, see the article *Codex Sangermanensis I*.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Second Esdras turns around a radical spiritual conversion of Ezra in a vision, where he stops to comfort a sobbing woman who turns instantly into a great city (2 Esd.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The following verses (10:28–59) reveal that Ezra had a vision of the heavenly Jerusalem, the true city of Zion, which the angel of the Lord invites him to explore.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The last two chapters, also called 6 Ezra by scholars, and found in the Latin, but not in the Eastern texts, predict wars and rebuke sinners.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Many assume that they probably date from a much later period (perhaps late third century) and may be Christian in origin; though not certain, they possibly were added at the same time as the first two chapters of the Latin version.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] They likely are Jewish in origin, however; 15:57–59 have been found in Greek, which most scholars agree was translated from a Hebrew original.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The main body of the book appears to be written for consolation in a period of great distress (one scholarly hypothesis is that it dates to Titus' destruction of the Second Temple in 70 CE).
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The author seeks answers, similar to Job's quest for understanding the meaning of suffering, but the author does not like or desire only the answer that was given to Job.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Critics question whether even the main body of the book, not counting the chapters that exist only in the Latin version and in Greek fragments, has a single author.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Kalisch, De Faye, and Charles hold that no fewer than five people worked on the text.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] However, Gunkel points to the unity in character and holds that the book is written by a single author; the author of 2 Esdras has also been suggested to have written the Syriac Apocalypse of Baruch.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] In any case, the two texts may date from about the same time, and one almost certainly depends on the other.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Critics have widely debated the origin of the book.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Hidden under two layers of translation, determining whether the author was Roman, Alexandrian, or Judean is impossible.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The book is found in the Orthodox Slavonic Bible (Ostrog Bible, Elizabeth Bible, and later consequently Russian Synodal Bible).
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] 2 Esdras is in the Apocrypha of the King James Version, and Pope Clement VIII placed it in an appendix to the Vulgate along with 3 Esdras and the Prayer of Manasseh "lest they perish entirely".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The chapters corresponding to 4 Ezra, i.e.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] 2 Esdras 3–14, make up the *Book of II Izra*, aka *Izra Sutuel*, canonical in the Orthodox Tewahedo churches; it was also widely cited by the early Church Fathers, particularly Ambrose, as the 'third book of Esdras'.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] It may also be found in many larger English Bibles included as part of the Biblical apocrypha, as they exist in the King James Version, the Revised Version, the Revised Standard Version, and the earliest editions of the Catholic Douay–Rheims Bible, among others.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The *introitus* of the traditional Requiem of the Extraordinary Form of the 1962 Tridentine Missal of the Catholic Church is loosely based on 2:34–35: "Eternal rest grant unto them, O Lord, and let perpetual light shine upon them." Several other liturgical prayers are taken from the book.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The same chapter, verses 36 and 37, is cited in the Introit of Pentecost Tuesday, "*Accipite jucunditatem gloriae vestrae, alleluia: gratias agentes Deo, alleluia: qui vos ad caelestia regna vocavit, alleluia, alleluia, alleluia*.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] 77 *Attendite, popule meus, legem meam: inclinate aurem vestram in verba oris mei.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Accipite*. – Receive the delight of your glory, alleluia, giving thanks to God, alleluia, Who hath called ye to the heavenly kingdoms, alleluia, alleluia, alleluia.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Psalm 77 Attend, O my people, to my law: incline your ears to the words of my mouth.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Receive.” The Alleluia verse *Crastina die* for the Vigil Mass of Christmas in the Roman Missal is taken from chapter 16, verse 52.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] Christopher Columbus quoted verse 6:42, which describes the Earth as created with six parts land and one part water, in his appeal to the Catholic Monarchs for financial support for his first voyage of exploration.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The book is appointed as a scripture reading in the Ordinariate’s Evensong service for All Hallows' Eve.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2-esdras] The work is included in the New Revised Standard Version-based *The Life with God Study Bible*.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] American Christian radio host Harold Camping stated in his 2005 book *Time Has an End* that the rapture and Judgment Day would take place on May 21, 2011, and that the end of the world would take place five months later on October 21, 2011.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping, who was then president of the Family Radio Christian network, claimed the Bible as his source and said May 21 would be the date of the rapture and the day of judgment "beyond the shadow of a doubt".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping suggested that it would occur at 6 p.m. local time, with the rapture sweeping the globe time zone by time zone, while some of his supporters claimed that around 200 million people (approximately 3% of the world's population) would be 'raptured'.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping had, in the early 1990s, posited that the rapture might occur in September 1994.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] The vast majority of Christian groups, including most Protestant and Catholic believers, did not accept Camping's predictions; some explicitly rejected them, citing Bible passages including the words of Jesus stating "about that day or hour no one knows" (Matthew 24:36).
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] An interview with a group of church leaders noted that all of them had scheduled church services as usual for Sunday, May 22.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Following the failure of the prediction, media attention shifted to the response from Camping and his followers.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] On May 23, Camping stated that May 21 had been a "spiritual" day of judgment, and that the physical rapture would occur on October 21, 2011, simultaneously with the destruction of the universe by God.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] However, on October 16, Camping admitted to an interviewer that he did not know when the end would come, and made no public comment after October 21 passed without his predicted apocalypse.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] In March 2012, Camping "humbly acknowledged" in a letter to Family Radio listeners that he had been mistaken, that the attempt to predict a date was "sinful", and that critics had been right in pointing to the scriptural text "of that day and hour knoweth no man".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] He added that he was searching the Bible "even more fervently [...] not to find dates, but to be more faithful in our understanding".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping presented several arguments labeled "numerological" by the mainstream media, which he considered biblical proofs, in favor of the May 21 end time.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] A civil engineer by training, Camping stated he had attempted to work out mathematically based prophecies in the Bible for decades.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] In an interview with the *San Francisco Chronicle* he explained "...
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] I was an engineer, I was very interested in the numbers.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] In 1970, Camping dated the Great Flood to 4990 BC.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping takes the 17th day of the second month mentioned in Genesis 7:11 to be May 21, and hence predicts the rapture to occur on this date.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] The number of days (as calculated below) between April 1, 33 AD, and May 21, 2011, AD, is 722,500.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] If 1,978 is multiplied by 365.2422 days (the number of days in a solar, as distinct from lunar, year), the result is 722,449.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] The time between April 1 and May 21 is 51 days.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping was not precise about the timing of the event, saying that "maybe" we can know the hour.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] He has suggested that "days" in the Bible refer to daylight hours particularly.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] In Camping's book *1994?*, self-published in 1992, he predicted that the end times would come on September 6, 1994.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] When the rapture failed to occur on the appointed day, Camping said he had made a mathematical error.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping's rapture prediction, along with some of his other teachings and beliefs, sparked controversy in the Christian and secular Western worlds.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] His critics often quoted Bible verses (such as Matthew 24:36) they interpret as saying that the date of the end will never be known by anyone but God until it actually happens.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] However, Camping and his followers responded that this principle applied only during the "church age" or pre-Tribulation period and did not apply to the present day, citing other verses (such as 1 Thessalonians 5:1–5:5) in their rebuttal.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] In a 2001 pamphlet, Camping asserted that believers should "flee the church", resigning from any church they belong to, because the "Church Age" is over and the "Great Tribulation" has begun.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] This assertion was controversial and drew "a flurry of attacks".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Yamauchi critiqued Camping's dating of the Flood when Camping first published his ideas in 1970.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Criticism of the May 21 prediction ranged from serious critique to ridicule.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Skinner, writing at the *Huffington Post*, noted the "long history of failed speculation" about the end times and cautioned that end-of-the-world talk can lead Christians to social passivity instead of "working for the world's redemption".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Some columnists mocked the prediction with humorous essays.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] In 2010, Marie Exley of Colorado Springs made news by purchasing advertising space in her locality, promoting the alleged rapture date on a number of park benches.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] After that, more than 5000 "Judgment Day" billboards were erected in locations across the world, including the Dominican Republic, Ethiopia, Ghana, Indonesia, Israel, Jamaica, Jordan, Lebanon, Lesotho, the Philippines, Tanzania and the United States.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Some people adorned their vehicles with the information.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Many who believed in the prediction took time off work to prepare for the Rapture.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Others spent their life savings on advertising material to publicize the prophecy.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] One retired transportation agency worker from New York spent $140,000 on advertising.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Family Radio spent over US$100 million on the information campaign, financed by sales and swap of broadcast outlets.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] According to former Family Radio employee Matt Tuter, "We had a pool of about $100 million dollars, and [Camping] spent it like no tomorrow." On October 27, 2010, they launched "Project Caravan".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Five recreational vehicles announcing on their sides that Judgment Day was to begin on May 21, 2011, were sent out from their headquarters in Oakland, California, to Seattle, Washington.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Upon arrival, teams were sent out to distribute tracts.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] The caravan subsequently made stops in many states in the U.S. and Canada.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping's prediction and his promotion of it via his radio network and other promotional means spread the prediction globally.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Some followers of Camping gave up their jobs, sold their homes, stopped investing in their children's college funds and spent large sums promoting Camping's claims.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] About 5,000 ethnic Hmong gathered at a remote town in Vietnam's Mường Nhé District in Điện Biên Province in early May, where they planned to await the arrival of Christ.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] The Vietnamese government broke up the gathering and arrested some people, describing them as "extremists".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Pastor Doan Trung Tin indicated that a translated version of Camping's prediction had influenced about 300 of his parishioners to go to the assembly point, selling their belongings to be able to afford the journey via bus.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Many of the Hmong Christians who escaped arrest were reportedly forced into hiding after the gathering.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] On May 19, 2011, the search term "end of the world may 21st" reached second position on Google Trends, based on the popularity of the search term in the United States.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] The related searches "Harold Camping", "May 21 doomsday", and "May 21 rapture" were also represented among the top 10 positions.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] The New York Police Department stated: "We don't plan any additional coverage for the end of the world.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] On the weekend of May 21–22, the Family Radio headquarters was closed with a note stating, "This office is closed.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Sorry we missed you!" The Family Radio network remained on the air during May 21 and May 22, mostly broadcasting its normal schedule of programming, but with no mention of the rapture and without the usual replays of Harold Camping's program *Open Forum*.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] On Sunday, May 22, Camping emerged briefly from his home, saying "Give me a day, no interviews today ...
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] I've got to live with it, I've got to think it out." He said he would make a public statement on Monday, May 23.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping said he was "flabbergasted" that the rapture did not occur, that he was "looking for answers", and would say more when he returned to work on May 23.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] On May 23, he returned to his *Open Forum* radio program, with members of the press in attendance, and, departing from his typical format, took questions from the reporters present instead of from callers.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] He stated that May 21 had been an "invisible judgment day" which was purely spiritual in nature, and that he now realized that the physical rapture would take place on October 21, simultaneously with the destruction of the universe.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] "We've always said May 21 was the day, but we didn't understand altogether the spiritual meaning," he said.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] He said that the publicity campaign would not continue, explaining that since God's judgment had already occurred, there was no point in continuing to warn people about it.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] He added, "We're not going to put up any more billboards – in fact they're coming down right now." Responding to a question, Camping said his organization would not return money donated by followers to publicize the May 21 prediction, saying "We're not at the end.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] A Family Radio staffer suggested that the delay might be God's way of separating true believers from those willing to doubt the "clear biblical warnings".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Individual followers who had spent time and money promoting Camping's prediction were "crestfallen" after May 21 passed without evidence of the rapture.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] A New York man commented "I was doing what I've been instructed to do through the Bible, but now I've been stymied.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] There were rumors that people had killed themselves or attempted suicide to escape the predicted Judgment Day.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] There was one documented case, in which a 14-year-old Russian girl killed herself on May 21.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Her family told a Russian tabloid, *LifeNews*, that she did it because of her fear of the "terrible sufferings" predicted by Camping.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] A group from the Calvary Bible Church in Milpitas, California offered a session to comfort those who had believed in the prophecy.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Church deacon James Bynum told a local newspaper that "We are here because we care about these people.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] In response to the prediction, more than 830,000 registered as attending a "Post Rapture Looting" event on Facebook.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] The group American Atheists sponsored billboards in several American cities declaring the rapture to be "nonsense".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] The group Seattle Atheists formed the Rapture Relief Fund which they said would be used "to help survivors of any Armageddon-sized disaster in the Puget Sound area"; since the rapture failed to occur on May 21, the money will fund a camp that teaches children about science and critical thinking.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] The comic strip *Doonesbury* spent the week leading up to the predicted day making fun of the prediction.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] On May 21, groups of protesters gathered at Family Radio's headquarters in Oakland to mock the evangelical broadcaster's failed prediction.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] One group released human-shaped helium balloons to simulate souls rising to heaven, while another person played The Doors' song "The End" over a boombox.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Many atheist and secular groups in the United States hosted "Rapture parties" on May 21.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] American Atheists hosted a two-day conference over the May 21 weekend in Oakland, not far from Camping's radio station.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] President David Silverman commented, "We're going to poke fun at these people, but in the end we need to keep in mind that there are people being hurt here ...
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] We're hoping people look at this and learn to use their brains ... so we don't have an occurrence of this in 2012" (when some believed the Maya predicted as the Earth's final destruction).
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Nickel Creek's album *A Dotted Line* features a song entitled "21st of May" that is based on the prediction.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping continued to predict that October 21 would mark the end of the world, based on adding the 153 fish of John 21:11 to May 21, but modified his prediction with words like *probably* and *maybe*.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] "I really am beginning to think as I've restudied these matters that there's going to be no big display of any kind," Camping said in a podcast.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] No statement was issued by Camping or Family Radio on October 21 or 22.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] It was later reported that Camping told an interviewer on October 16 that God has not given anyone the power to know exactly when the rapture would come.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] He retired from his leadership position at Family Radio.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Sometime after October 21, Family Radio posted an audio message from Harold Camping on their home page.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] In the message, Camping stated, regarding end times prophecy, that "we are finding it very very difficult".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] He also told followers to "not feel abandoned by God" and that "God is still in charge of everything".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] As October 21 approached, the Freedom from Religion Foundation bought space on more than 40 billboards in the Bay Area to mock Camping's predictions and urge viewers to use rational judgment.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] The billboards featured slogans such as, "Fool me once...", "Still here", and "Every day is judgment day.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Media reports on October 21 and 22 stressed that Camping had been "wrong again".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] The *International Business Times* proclaimed him a "false prophet".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] On October 21, 2011, *Time* magazine's website listed Camping's end times predictions as one of the "Top 10 Failed Predictions", a list compiled in Camping's "honor".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Family Radio removed from its web site the archive of audio recordings of Camping's Open Forum program recorded prior to May 2011.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] On June 9, 2011, Camping suffered a stroke and was hospitalized.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Family Radio broadcast reruns of his May 23 – June 9 *Open Forum* segments for several weeks.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] As of June 23, Family Radio began to provide new programming in his time slot.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] In April 2012, Family Radio sold its Philadelphia station WKDN to Merlin Media; upon its formal takeover of the station, WKDN broadcast the R.E.M. song "It's the End of the World as We Know It (And I Feel Fine)" for several hours as a stunt referencing the failed prediction.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping died on December 15, 2013, at the age of 92, as a result of complications from a fall at home two weeks earlier.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] His death was confirmed by an employee of the network.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] In September 2018, Family Radio announced it would no longer air programs featuring the voice of Harold Camping, and would no longer distribute literature of Camping's teachings.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] The decision was made as part of an effort to both move away from Camping's theology, and to reintroduce programs from outside ministries into the network's schedule.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] The changes went into effect on October 8, 2018.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] McCann continued to teach that October 21, 2011, would be the end of the world, even after the failed May 21, 2011 prediction.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] And after October 21, 2011, he taught that the end of the world would occur in March 2012.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] At the end of 2012, McCann began teaching the possibility that the last day would be October 7, 2015.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] He said that there was "a strong likelihood that this will happen" and "an unlikely possibility that it will not".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] According to his interpretation of 2 Peter 3, the world will be destroyed by fire.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Later, McCann said it was "surprising" that the world did not end at the predicted date.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] This date was arrived at by adding 1,600 days (taken from Revelation 14:20) to May 21, 2011, which McCann continued to teach at least well into 2012 was the beginning of the day of judgment.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] He noted that October 7, 2015, is the last day of the Feast of Tabernacles, and exactly 10,000 days from May 21, 1988, which he claims is the date the Church Age came to an end.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2011-end-times-prediction] Robert Fitzpatrick wrote a book entitled *The Doomsday Code*, based on the writings of Camping.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The **2012 phenomenon** was a range of eschatological beliefs that cataclysmic or transformative events would occur on or around 21 December 2012.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Various astronomical alignments and numerological formulae were proposed for this date.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] A New Age interpretation held that the date marked the start of a period during which Earth and its inhabitants would undergo a positive physical or spiritual transformation, and that 21 December 2012 would mark the beginning of a new era.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Others suggested that the date marked the end of the world or a similar catastrophe.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Scholars from various disciplines quickly dismissed predictions of cataclysmic events as they arose.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Mayan scholars stated that no classic Mayan accounts forecast impending doom, and the idea that the Long Count calendar ends in 2012 misrepresented Mayan history and culture.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Astronomers rejected the various proposed doomsday scenarios as pseudoscience, having been refuted by elementary astronomical observations.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] December 2012 marked the conclusion of a *bʼakʼtun*—a time period in the Mesoamerican Long Count calendar, used in Mesoamerica prior to the arrival of Europeans.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Although the Long Count was most likely invented by the Olmec, it has become closely associated with the Maya civilization, whose classic period lasted from 250 to 900 AD.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The writing system of the classic Maya has been substantially deciphered, meaning that a text corpus of their written and inscribed material has survived from before the Spanish conquest of Yucatán.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Thus, the Maya date of 8.3.2.10.15 represents 8 bʼakʼtuns, 3 kʼatuns, 2 tuns, 10 uinals and 15 days.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] There is a strong tradition of "world ages" in Maya literature, but the record has been distorted, leaving several possibilities open to interpretation.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] According to the *Popol Vuh*, a compilation of the creation accounts of the Kʼicheʼ Maya of the Colonial-era highlands, the current world is the fourth.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The *Popol Vuh* describes the gods first creating three failed worlds, followed by a successful fourth world in which humanity was placed.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In the Maya Long Count, the previous world ended after 13 bʼakʼtuns, or roughly 5,125 years.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The Long Count's "zero date" was set at a point in the past marking the end of the third world and the beginning of the current one, which corresponds to 11 August 3114 BC in the proleptic Gregorian calendar.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] This means that the fourth world reached the end of its 13th bʼakʼtun, or Maya date 13.0.0.0.0, on 21 December 2012.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In 1957, Mayanist and astronomer Maud Worcester Makemson wrote that "the completion of a Great Period of 13 bʼakʼtuns would have been of the utmost significance to the Maya." In 1966, Michael D.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Coe wrote in *The Maya* that "there is a suggestion ... that Armageddon would overtake the degenerate peoples of the world and all creation on the final day of the 13th [bʼakʼtun].
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Coe's interpretation was repeated by other scholars through the early 1990s.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In contrast, later researchers said that, while the end of the 13th bʼakʼtun would perhaps be a cause for celebration, it did not mark the end of the calendar.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] "There is nothing in the Maya or Aztec or ancient Mesoamerican prophecy to suggest that they prophesied a sudden or major change of any sort in 2012," said Mayanist scholar Mark Van Stone.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] "The notion of a 'Great Cycle' coming to an end is completely a modern invention." In 1990, Mayanist scholars Linda Schele and David Freidel argued that the Maya "did not conceive this to be the end of creation, as many have suggested".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Susan Milbrath, curator of Latin American Art and Archaeology at the Florida Museum of Natural History, stated that, "We have no record or knowledge that [the Maya] would think the world would come to an end" in 2012.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Wyllys Andrews V, director of the Tulane University Middle American Research Institute.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The Maya were looking for a guarantee that nothing would change.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Several prominent individuals representing Maya of Guatemala decried the suggestion that the world would end with the 13th bʼakʼtun.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Ricardo Cajas, president of the *Colectivo de Organizaciones Indígenas de Guatemala*, said the date did not represent an end of humanity but that the new cycle "supposes changes in human consciousness".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Martín Sacalxot, of the office of Guatemala's Human Rights Ombudsman (*Procurador de los Derechos Humanos*), said that the end of the calendar has nothing to do with the end of the world or the year 2012.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The European association of the Maya with eschatology dates back to the time of Christopher Columbus, who was compiling a work called *Libro de las profecías* during the voyage in 1502 when he first heard about the "Maia" on Guanaja, an island off the north coast of Honduras.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Influenced by the writings of Bishop Pierre d'Ailly, Columbus believed that his discovery of "most distant" lands (and, by extension, the Maya themselves) was prophesied and would bring about the Apocalypse.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] End-times fears were widespread during the early years of the Spanish Conquest as the result of popular astrological predictions in Europe of a second Great Flood for the year 1524.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In the 1900s, German scholar Ernst Förstemann interpreted the last page of the Dresden Codex as a representation of the end of the world in a cataclysmic flood.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] He made reference to the destruction of the world and an apocalypse, though he made no reference to the 13th bʼakʼtun or 2012 and it was not clear that he was referring to a future event.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] His ideas were repeated by archaeologist Sylvanus Morley, who directly paraphrased Förstemann and added his own embellishments, writing, "Finally, on the last page of the manuscript, is depicted the Destruction of the World ...
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Here, indeed, is portrayed with a graphic touch the final all-engulfing cataclysm" in the form of a great flood.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] These comments were later repeated in Morley's book, *The Ancient Maya*, the first edition of which was published in 1946.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] It is not certain what significance the classic Maya gave to the 13th bʼakʼtun.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Most classic Maya inscriptions are strictly historical and do not make any prophetic declarations.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Two items in the Maya classical corpus do mention the end of the 13th bʼakʼtun: Tortuguero Monument 6 and La Corona Hieroglyphic Stairway 12.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The Tortuguero site, which lies in southernmost Tabasco, Mexico, dates from the 7th century AD and consists of a series of inscriptions mostly in honor of the contemporary ruler Bahlam Ahau.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] One inscription, known as Tortuguero Monument 6, is the only inscription known to refer to bʼakʼtun 13 in any detail.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Very little is known about the god Bʼolon Yokteʼ.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] According to an article by Mayanists Markus Eberl and Christian Prager in *British Anthropological Reports*, his name is composed of the elements "nine", ʼOK-teʼ (the meaning of which is unknown), and "god".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Confusion in classical period inscriptions suggests that the name was already ancient and unfamiliar to contemporary scribes.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] He also appears in inscriptions from Palenque, Usumacinta, and La Mar as a god of war, conflict, and the underworld.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In one stele he is portrayed with a rope tied around his neck, and in another with an incense bag, together signifying a sacrifice to end a cycle of years.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Based on observations of modern Maya rituals, Gronemeyer and MacLeod claim that the stela refers to a celebration in which a person portraying Bolon Yokteʼ Kʼuh was wrapped in ceremonial garments and paraded around the site.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] They note that the association of Bolon Yokteʼ Kʼuh with bʼakʼtun 13 appears to be so important on this inscription that it supersedes more typical celebrations such as "erection of stelae, scattering of incense" and so forth.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Furthermore, they assert that this event was indeed planned for 2012 and not the 7th century.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Mayanist scholar Stephen Houston contests this view by arguing that future dates on Maya inscriptions were simply meant to draw parallels with contemporary events, and that the words on the stela describe a contemporary rather than a future scene.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In April–May 2012, a team of archaeologists unearthed a previously unknown inscription on a stairway at the La Corona site in Guatemala.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The inscription, on what is known as Hieroglyphic Stairway 12, describes the establishment of a royal court in Calakmul in 635 AD, and compares the then-recent completion of 13 kʼatuns with the future completion of the 13th bʼakʼtun.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] It contains no speculation or prophecy as to what the scribes believed would happen at that time.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Maya inscriptions occasionally mention predicted future events or commemorations that would occur on dates far beyond the completion of the 13th bʼakʼtun.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Most of these are in the form of "distance dates"; Long Count dates together with an additional number, known as a Distance Number, which when added to them makes a future date.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] On the west panel at the Temple of Inscriptions in Palenque, a section of text projects forward to the 80th 52-year Calendar Round from the coronation of the ruler Kʼinich Janaabʼ Pakal.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Pakal's accession occurred on 9.9.2.4.8, equivalent to 27 July 615 AD in the proleptic Gregorian calendar.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The inscription begins with Pakal's birthdate of 9.8.9.13.0 (24 March, 603 AD Gregorian) and then adds the Distance Number 10.11.10.5.8 to it, arriving at a date of 21 October 4772 AD, more than 4,000 years after Pakal's time.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] According to Linda Schele, these 13s represent "the starting point of a huge odometer of time", with each acting as a zero and resetting to 1 as the numbers increase.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Thus this inscription anticipates the current universe lasting at least 2021×13×360 days, or roughly 2.687×1028 years; a time span equal to 2 quintillion times the age of the universe as determined by cosmologists.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Others have suggested that this date marks creation as having occurred after that time span.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In 2012, researchers announced the discovery of a series of Maya astronomical tables in Xultún, Guatemala which plot the movements of the Moon and other astronomical bodies over the course of 17 bʼakʼtuns.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Many assertions about the year 2012 form part of Mayanism, a non-codified collection of New Age beliefs about ancient Maya wisdom and spirituality.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The term is distinct from "Mayanist," used to refer to an academic scholar of the Maya.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Archaeoastronomer Anthony Aveni says that while the idea of "balancing the cosmos" was prominent in ancient Maya literature, the 2012 phenomenon did not draw from those traditions.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Instead, it was bound up with American concepts such as the New Age movement, 2012 millenarianism, and the belief in secret knowledge from distant times and places.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Themes found in 2012 literature included "suspicion towards mainstream Western culture", the idea of spiritual evolution, and the possibility of leading the world into the New Age by individual example or by a group's joined consciousness.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The general intent of this literature was not to warn of impending doom but "to foster counter-cultural sympathies and eventually socio-political and 'spiritual' activism".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In 1975, the ending of bʼakʼtun 13 became the subject of speculation by several New Age authors, who asserted it would correspond with a global "transformation of consciousness".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Some research suggests that both Argüelles and McKenna were heavily influenced in this regard by the Mayanism of American author William S.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Burroughs, who first portrayed the end of the Mayan Long Count as an apocalyptic shift of human consciousness in 1960's *The Exterminator*.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In 1983, with the publication of Robert J.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Sharer's revised table of date correlations in the 4th edition of Morley's *The Ancient Maya,* each became convinced that 21 December 2012 had significant meaning.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] By 1987, the year in which he organized the Harmonic Convergence event, Argüelles was using the date 21 December 2012 in *The Mayan Factor: Path Beyond Technology*.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] He believed that the Maya aligned their calendar to correspond to this phenomenon.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Anthony Aveni has dismissed all of these ideas.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In 2001, Robert Bast wrote the first online articles regarding the possibility of a doomsday in 2012.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In 2006, author Daniel Pinchbeck popularized New Age concepts about this date in his book *2012: The Return of Quetzalcoatl*, linking bʼakʼtun 13 to beliefs in crop circles, alien abduction, and personal revelations based on the use of hallucinogenic drugs and mediumship.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Pinchbeck claims to discern a "growing realization that materialism and the rational, empirical worldview that comes with it has reached its expiration date ... [w]e're on the verge of transitioning to a dispensation of consciousness that's more intuitive, mystical and shamanic".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] There is no significant astronomical event tied to the Long Count's start date.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Its supposed end date was tied to astronomical phenomena by esoteric, fringe, and New Age literature that placed great significance on astrology, especially astrological interpretations associated with the phenomenon of axial precession.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Chief among these ideas is the astrological concept of a "galactic alignment".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In the Solar System, the planets and the Sun lie roughly within the same flat plane, known as the plane of the ecliptic.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] From our perspective on Earth, the ecliptic is the path taken by the Sun across the sky over the course of the year.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The twelve constellations that line the ecliptic are known as the zodiacal constellations, and, annually, the Sun passes through all of them in turn.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Additionally, over time, the Sun's annual cycle appears to recede very slowly backward by one degree every 72 years, or by one constellation approximately every 2,160 years.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] This backward movement, called "precession", is due to a slight wobble in the Earth's axis as it spins, and can be compared to the way a spinning top wobbles as it slows down.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Over the course of 25,800 years, a period often called a Great Year, the Sun's path completes a full, 360-degree backward rotation through the zodiac.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In Western astrological traditions, precession is measured from the March equinox, one of the two annual points at which the Sun is exactly halfway between its lowest and highest points in the sky.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] At the end of the 20th century and beginning of the 21st, the Sun's March equinox position was in the constellation Pisces moving back into Aquarius.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] This signaled the end of one astrological age (the Age of Pisces) and the beginning of another (the Age of Aquarius).
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Similarly, the Sun's December solstice position (in the northern hemisphere, the lowest point on its annual path; in the southern hemisphere, the highest) was in the constellation of Sagittarius, one of two constellations in which the zodiac intersects with the Milky Way.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Every year, on the December solstice, the Sun and the Milky Way, appear (from the surface of the Earth) to come into alignment, and every year precession caused a slight shift in the Sun's position in the Milky Way.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Given that the Milky Way is between 10° and 20° wide, it takes between 700 and 1,400 years for the Sun's December solstice position to precess through it.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In 2012 it was about halfway through the Milky Way, crossing the galactic equator.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In 2012, the Sun's December solstice fell on 21 December.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Mystical speculations about the precession of the equinoxes and the Sun's proximity to the center of the Milky Way appeared in *Hamlet's Mill* (1969) by Giorgio de Santillana and Hertha von Deschend.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] These were quoted and expanded upon by Terence and Dennis McKenna in *The Invisible Landscape* (1975).
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Adherents to the idea, following a theory first proposed by Munro Edmonson, alleged that the Maya based their calendar on observations of the Great Rift or Dark Rift, a band of dark dust clouds in the Milky Way, which, according to some scholars, the Maya called the *Xibalba be* or "Black Road".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] John Major Jenkins claims that the Maya were aware of where the ecliptic intersected the Black Road and gave this position in the sky a special significance in their cosmology.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Jenkins said that precession would align the Sun precisely with the galactic equator at the 2012 winter solstice.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Jenkins claimed that the classical Maya anticipated this conjunction and celebrated it as the harbinger of a profound spiritual transition for mankind.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] New Age proponents of the galactic alignment hypothesis argued that, just as astrology uses the positions of stars and planets to make claims of future events, the Maya plotted their calendars with the objective of preparing for significant world events.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Jenkins attributed the insights of ancient Maya shamans about the Galactic Center to their use of psilocybin mushrooms, psychoactive toads, and other psychedelics.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Jenkins also associated the *Xibalba be* with a "world tree", drawing on studies of contemporary (not ancient) Maya cosmology.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Astronomers such as David Morrison argue that the galactic equator is an entirely arbitrary line and can never be precisely drawn, because it is impossible to determine the Milky Way's exact boundaries, which vary depending on clarity of view.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Jenkins claimed he drew his conclusions about the location of the galactic equator from observations taken at above 11,000 feet (3,400 m), an altitude that gives a clearer image of the Milky Way than the Maya had access to.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Furthermore, since the Sun is half a degree wide, its solstice position takes 36 years to precess its full width.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Jenkins himself noted that even given his determined location for the line of the galactic equator, its most precise convergence with the center of the Sun already occurred in 1998, and so asserts that, rather than 2012, the galactic alignment instead focuses on a multi-year period centered in 1998.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] There is no clear evidence that the classic Maya were aware of precession.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Some Maya scholars, such as Barbara MacLeod, Michael Grofe, Eva Hunt, Gordon Brotherston, and Anthony Aveni, have suggested that some Mayan holy dates were timed to precessional cycles, but scholarly opinion on the subject remains divided.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] There is also little evidence, archaeological or historical, that the Maya placed any importance on solstices or equinoxes.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] It is possible that only the earliest among Mesoamericans observed solstices, but this is also a disputed issue among Mayanists.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] There is also no evidence that the classic Maya attached any importance to the Milky Way; there is no glyph in their writing system to represent it, and no astronomical or chronological table tied to it.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] "Timewave zero" is a numerological formula that purports to calculate the ebb and flow of "novelty", defined as increase over time in the universe's interconnectedness, or organized complexity.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Terence McKenna claimed that the universe has a teleological attractor at the end of time that increases interconnectedness.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] He believed this which would eventually reach a singularity of infinite complexity in 2012, at which point anything and everything imaginable would occur simultaneously.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] He conceived this idea over several years in the early to mid-1970s whilst using psilocybin mushrooms and DMT.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The scientific community considers novelty theory to be pseudoscience.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] McKenna expressed "novelty" in a computer program which produces a waveform known as "timewave zero" or the "timewave".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Based on McKenna's interpretation of the King Wen sequence of the *I Ching*, an ancient Chinese book on divination, the graph purports to show great periods of novelty corresponding with major shifts in humanity's biological and sociocultural evolution.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] He believed that the events of any given time are resonantly related to the events of other times, and chose the atomic bombing of Hiroshima as the basis for calculating his end date of November 2012.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] When he later discovered this date's proximity to the end of the 13th bʼakʼtun of the Maya calendar, he revised his hypothesis so that the two dates matched.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The 1975 first edition of *The Invisible Landscape* referred to 2012 (but no specific day during the year) only twice.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In the 1993 second edition, McKenna employed Sharer's date of 21 December 2012 throughout.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The idea that the year 2012 presaged a world cataclysm, the end of the world, or the end of human civilization, became a subject of popular media speculation as the date of 21 December 2012 approached.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] This idea was promulgated by many pages on the Internet, particularly on YouTube.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The Discovery Channel was criticized for its "quasi-documentaries" about the subject that "sacrifice[d] accuracy for entertainment".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Some people interpreted the galactic alignment apocalyptically, claiming that its occurrence would somehow create a combined gravitational effect between the Sun and the supermassive black hole at the center of our galaxy (known as Sagittarius A*), creating havoc on Earth.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Apart from the "galactic alignment" already having happened in 1998, the Sun's apparent path through the zodiac as seen from Earth did not take it near the true galactic center, but rather several degrees above it.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Even were this not the case, Sagittarius A* is 30,000 light years from Earth; it would have to have been more than 6 million times closer to cause any gravitational disruption to Earth's Solar System.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] This reading of the alignment was included on the History Channel documentary *Decoding the Past*.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] John Major Jenkins complained that a science fiction writer co-authored the documentary, and he went on to characterize it as "45 minutes of unabashed doomsday hype and the worst kind of inane sensationalism".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Some believers in a 2012 doomsday used the term "galactic alignment" to describe a different phenomenon proposed by some scientists to explain a pattern in mass extinctions supposedly observed in the fossil record.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] According to the Shiva hypothesis, mass extinctions are not random, but recur every 26 million years.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] To account for this, it was suggested that vertical oscillations made by the Sun on its 250-million-year orbit of the galactic center cause it to regularly pass through the galactic plane.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] When the Sun's orbit takes it outside the galactic plane which bisects the galactic disc, the influence of the galactic tide is weaker.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] This "alignment" takes place over tens of millions of years, and could never be timed to an exact date.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Evidence shows that the Sun passed through the plane bisecting the galactic disc three million years ago and in 2012 was moving farther above it.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] A third suggested alignment was some sort of planetary conjunction occurring on 21 December 2012; there was no conjunction on that date.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Multi-planet alignments did occur in both 2000 and 2010, each with no ill result for the Earth.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Jupiter is the largest planet in the Solar System, being larger than all other planets combined.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] When Jupiter is near opposition, the difference in gravitational force that the Earth experiences is less than 1% of the force that the Earth feels daily from the Moon.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Another idea tied to 2012 involved a geomagnetic reversal (often referred to as a pole shift by proponents), possibly triggered by a massive solar flare, that would release an energy equal to 100 billion atomic bombs.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] This belief was supposedly supported by observations that the Earth's magnetic field was weakening, which could precede a reversal of the north and south magnetic poles, and the arrival of the next solar maximum, which was expected sometime around 2012.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Most scientific estimates say that geomagnetic reversals take between 1,000 and 10,000 years to complete, and do not start on any particular date.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration predicted that the solar maximum would peak in late 2013 or 2014, and that it would be fairly weak, with a below-average number of sunspots.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] There was no scientific evidence linking a solar maximum to a geomagnetic reversal, which is driven by forces entirely within the Earth.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] A solar maximum does affect satellite and cellular phone communications.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] On 23 July 2012, a massive, potentially damaging, solar storm came within nine days of striking Earth.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Some believers in a 2012 doomsday claimed that a planet called Planet X, or Nibiru, would collide with or pass by the Earth.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] This idea, which had appeared in various forms since 1995, initially predicted Doomsday in May 2003, but proponents abandoned that date after it passed without incident.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The idea originated from claims of channeling alien beings and is widely ridiculed.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Astronomers calculated that such an object so close to Earth would be visible to anyone looking up at the night sky.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Author Graham Hancock, in his book *Fingerprints of the Gods*, interpreted Coe's remarks in *Breaking the Maya Code* as evidence for the prophecy of a global cataclysm.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Filmmaker Roland Emmerich later credited the book with inspiring his 2009 disaster film *2012*.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Other speculations regarding doomsday in 2012 included predictions by the Web Bot project, a computer program that purports to predict the future by analyzing Internet chatter.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Commentators have rejected claims that the bot is able to predict natural disasters, as opposed to human-caused disasters like stock market crashes.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The 2012 date was also loosely tied to the long-running concept of the **photon belt**, which predicted a form of interaction between Earth and Alcyone, the largest star of the Pleiades cluster.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Critics argued that photons cannot form belts, that the Pleiades, located more than 400 light years away, could have no effect on Earth, and that the Solar System, rather than getting closer to the Pleiades, was in fact moving farther away from it.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Some media outlets tied the fact that the red supergiant star Betelgeuse would undergo a supernova at some point in the future to the 2012 phenomenon.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] While Betelgeuse was certainly in the final stages of its life, and would die as a supernova, there was no way to predict the timing of the event to within 100,000 years.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] To be a threat to Earth, a supernova would need to be no further than 25 light years from the Solar System.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Betelgeuse is roughly 600 light years away, and so its supernova would not affect Earth.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In December 2011, NASA's Francis Reddy issued a press release debunking the possibility of a supernova occurring in 2012.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In December 2010, an article, first published in examiner.com and later referenced in the English-language edition of *Pravda* claimed, citing a Second Digitized Sky Survey photograph as evidence, that SETI had detected three large spacecraft due to arrive at Earth in 2012.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Astronomer and debunker Phil Plait noted that by using the small-angle formula, one could determine that if the object in the photo were as large as claimed, it would have had to be closer to Earth than the Moon, which would mean it would already have arrived.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In January 2011, Seth Shostak, chief astronomer of SETI, issued a press release debunking the claims.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The phenomenon spread widely after coming to public notice, particularly on the Internet, and hundreds of thousands of websites made reference to it.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] "Ask an Astrobiologist", a NASA public outreach website, received over 5,000 questions from the public on the subject from 2007, some asking whether they should kill themselves, their children or their pets.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] At least one suicide was directly linked to fear of a 2012 apocalypse, with others anecdotally reported.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Jared Lee Loughner, the perpetrator of the 2011 Tucson shooting, followed 2012-related predictions.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] A panel of scientists questioned on the topic at a plenary session at the Astronomical Society of the Pacific contended that the Internet played a substantial role in allowing this doomsday date to gain more traction than previous similar panics.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Beginning in 2000, the small French village of Bugarach, population 189, began receiving visits from "esoterics"—mystic believers who had concluded that the local mountain, Pic de Bugarach, was the ideal location to weather the transformative events of 2012.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In 2011, the local mayor, Jean-Pierre Delord, began voicing fears to the international press that the small town would be overwhelmed by an influx of thousands of visitors in 2012, even suggesting he might call in the army.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] "We've seen a huge rise in visitors", Delord told *The Independent* in March 2012.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] "Already this year more than 20,000 people have climbed right to the top, and last year we had 10,000 hikers, which was a significant rise on the previous 12 months.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] They think Pic de Bugarach is 'un garage à ovnis' [a garage for UFOs].
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The villagers are exasperated: the exaggerated importance of something which they see as completely removed from reality is bewildering.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] After 21 December, this will surely return to normal." In December 2012, the French government placed 100 police and firefighters around both Bugarach and Pic de Bugarach, limiting access to potential visitors.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Ultimately, only about 1,000 visitors appeared at the height of the "event".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Two raves were foiled, 12 people had to be turned away from the peak, and 5 people were arrested for carrying weapons.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Jean-Pierre Delord was criticised by members of the community for failing to take advantage of the media attention and promote the region.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The Turkish village of Şirince, near Ephesus, expected to receive over 60,000 visitors on 21 December 2012, as New Age mystics believed its "positive energy" would aid in weathering the catastrophe.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Only a fraction of that number actually arrived, with a substantial component being police and journalists, and the expected windfall failed to materialise.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Similarly, the pyramid-like mountain of Rtanj, in the Serbian Carpathians, attracted attention, due to rumors that it would emit a powerful force shield on the day, protecting those in the vicinity.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In Russia, inmates of a women's prison experienced "a collective mass psychosis" in the weeks leading up to the supposed doomsday, while residents of a factory town near Moscow reportedly emptied a supermarket of matches, candles, food and other supplies.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The Minister of Emergency Situations declared in response that according to "methods of monitoring what is occurring on the planet Earth", there would be no apocalypse in December.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In December 2012, Vatican astronomer Rev.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] José Funes wrote in the Vatican newspaper *L'Osservatore Romano* that apocalyptic theories around 2012 were "not even worth discussing".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In May 2011, 5,000-7,000 Hmong ethnic people in Dien Bien province, Vietnam held a protest on the grounds that the end of the world was coming, and the Hmong people would be evacuated to their own Hmong country by "supernatural force".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The Vietnamese media and government believe that this is a trick of the Hmong ethnic separatist forces.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In China, up to a thousand members of the Christian cult Almighty God were arrested after claiming that the end of bʼakʼtun 13 marked the end of the world, and that it was time to overthrow Communism.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Shoppers were reported to be hoarding supplies of candles in anticipation of coming darkness, while online retailer Taobao sold tickets to board Noah's Ark to customers.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Bookings for wedding ceremonies on 21 December 2012 were saturated in several cities.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] On 14 December 2012, a man in Henan province attacked and wounded twenty-three children with a knife.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Authorities suspected the man had been "influenced" by the prediction of the upcoming apocalypse.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Academics in China attributed the widespread belief in the 2012 doomsday in their country to a lack of scientific literacy and a mistrust of the government-controlled media.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] On 6 December 2012, Australian Prime Minister Julia Gillard delivered a hoax speech for the radio station triple J in which she declared "My dear remaining fellow Australians; the end of the world is coming.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Jasper Tsang, president of Hong Kong's Legislative Council, adjourned the legislature's sitting on 20 December 2012 by announcing that he "would not permit the world to end" as the legislature had to meet again in January 2013, to the laughter of MPs.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Mesoamerican countries that once formed part of the Maya civilization—Mexico, Belize, Guatemala, Honduras, and El Salvador—all organized festivities to commemorate the end of bʼakʼtun 13 at the largest Maya sites.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] On 21 December 2011, the Maya town of Tapachula in Chiapas activated an eight-foot digital clock counting down the days until the end of bʼakʼtun 13.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] On 21 December 2012, major events took place at Chichén Itzá in Mexico and Tikal in Guatemala.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In El Salvador, the largest event was held at Tazumal, and in Honduras, at Copán.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In all of these archaeological sites, Maya rituals were held at dawn led by shamans and Maya priests.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] On the final day of bʼakʼtun 13, residents of Yucatán and other regions formerly dominated by the ancient Maya celebrated what they saw as the dawn of a new, better era.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] According to official figures from Mexico's National Institute of Anthropology and History (INAH), about 50,000 people visited Mexican archaeological sites on 21 December 2012.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Of those, 10,000 visited Chichén Itzá in Yucatán, 9,900 visited Tulum in Quintana Roo, and 8,000 visited Palenque in Chiapas.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] An additional 10,000 people visited Teotihuacan near Mexico City, which is not a Maya site.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The main ceremony in Chichén Itzá was held at dawn in the plaza of the Temple of Kukulkán, one of the principal symbols of Maya culture.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The archaeological site was opened two hours early to receive thousands of tourists, mostly foreigners who came to participate in events scheduled for the end of bʼakʼtun 13.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The fire ceremony at Tikal was held at dawn in the main plaza of the Temple of the Great Jaguar.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The ceremony was led by Guatemalan and foreign priests.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The President of Guatemala, Otto Pérez, and of Costa Rica, Laura Chinchilla, participated in the event as special guests.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] During the ceremony the priests asked for unity, peace and the end of discrimination and racism, with the hope that the start of a new cycle will be a "new dawn".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] About 3,000 people participated in the event.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Most of these events were organized by agencies of the Mexican and Central American governments, and their respective tourism industries expected to attract thousands of visitors.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Mexico is visited by about 22 million foreigners in a typical year.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In 2012, the national tourism agency expected to attract 52 million visitors just to the regions of Chiapas, Yucatán, Quintana Roo, Tabasco and Campeche.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] A Maya activist group in Guatemala, Oxlaljuj Ajpop, objected to the commercialization of the date.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] A spokesman from the Conference of Maya Ministers commented that for them the Tikal ceremony is not a show for tourists but something spiritual and personal.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The secretary of the Great Council of Ancestral Authorities commented that living Maya felt they were excluded from the activities in Tikal.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] This group held a parallel ceremony, and complained that the date has been used for commercial gain.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In addition, before the main Tikal ceremony, about 200 Maya protested the celebration because they felt excluded.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Most modern Maya were indifferent to the ceremonies, and the small number of people still practising ancient rites held solemn, more private ceremonies.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Osvaldo Gomez, a technical advisor to the Tikal site, complained that many visitors during the celebration had illegally climbed the stairs of the Temple of the Masks, causing "irreparable" damage.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In Brazil, Décio Colla, the Mayor of the City of São Francisco de Paula, Rio Grande do Sul, mobilized the population to prepare for the end of the world by stocking up on food and supplies.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In the city of Corguinho, in the Mato Grosso do Sul, a colony was built for survivors of the expected tragedy.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In Alto Paraíso de Goiás, the hotels also made specific reservations for prophetic dates.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In Bolivia, President Evo Morales participated in Quechua and Aymara rituals, organized with government support, to commemorate the Southern solstice that took place in Isla del Sol, in the southern part of Lake Titicaca.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] During the event, Morales proclaimed the beginning of "*Pachakuti*", meaning the world's wake up to a culture of life and the beginning of the end to world capitalism, and he proposed to dismantle the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] On 21 December 2012, the Uritorco mountain in Córdoba, Argentina was closed, as a mass suicide there had been proposed on Facebook.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In the United States, sales of private underground blast shelters increased noticeably after 2009, with many construction companies' advertisements calling attention to the 2012 apocalypse.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In Michigan, schools were closed for the Christmas holidays two days early, in part because rumours of the 2012 apocalypse were raising fears of repeat shootings similar to that at Sandy Hook.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] American reality TV stars Heidi Montag and Spencer Pratt revealed that they had spent most of their $10 million of accumulated earnings by 2010 because they believed the world would end in 2012.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The 2012 phenomenon was discussed or referenced by several media outlets.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Several TV documentaries, as well as some contemporary fictional references to the year 2012, referred to 21 December as the day of a cataclysmic event.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The TV series *The X-Files* cited 22 December 2012 as the date for an alien colonization of the Earth, and mentioned the Mayan calendar "stopping" on this date.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The History Channel aired a handful of special series on doomsday that included analysis of 2012 theories, such as *Decoding the Past* (2005–2007), *2012, End of Days* (2006), *Last Days on Earth* (2006), *Seven Signs of the Apocalypse* (2009), and *Nostradamus 2012* (2008).
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The Discovery Channel also aired *2012 Apocalypse* in 2009, suggesting that massive solar storms, magnetic pole reversal, earthquakes, supervolcanoes, and other drastic natural events could occur in 2012.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In 2012, the National Geographic Channel launched a show called *Doomsday Preppers*, a documentary series about survivalists preparing for various cataclysms, including the 2012 doomsday.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Hundreds of books were published on the topic.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The bestselling book of 2009, Dan Brown's *The Lost Symbol*, featured a coded mock email number (2456282.5) that decoded to the Julian date for 21 December 2012.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In the Ubisoft game franchise *Assassin's Creed*, the overarching plotline of the games starring the first protagonist, Desmond Miles, was also inspired by the phenomenon.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] After escaping capture by the Knights Templar, Desmond rejoins the Assassins Brotherhood to help them fight the Templars and prevent the predicted end of the world, in this case caused by a cyclical solar flare.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] As these promotions did not mention the film itself, many viewers believed them to be real and contacted astronomers in panic.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Although the campaign was criticized, the film became one of the most successful of its year, grossing nearly $770 million worldwide.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] An article in *The Daily Telegraph* attributed the widespread fear of the phenomenon in China to the film, which was a hit in the country as it depicted the Chinese building "survival arks".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Lars von Trier's 2011 film *Melancholia* featured a plot in which a planet emerges from behind the Sun on a collision course with Earth.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The phenomenon also inspired several rock and pop music hits.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] As early as 1997, "A Certain Shade of Green" by Incubus referred to the mystical belief that a shift in perception would arrive in 2012 ("Are you gonna stand around till 2012 A.D.? / What are you waiting for, a certain shade of green?").
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Towards mid-December 2012, an internet hoax related to South Korean singer Psy being one of the Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse was widely circulated around social media platforms.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The hoax purported that once Psy's "Gangnam Style" YouTube video amassed a billion views, the world would end.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] Rahman, known for *Slumdog Millionaire*, released his single "Infinite Love" to "instill faith and optimism in people" prior to the hypothesized doomsday.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The artwork for All Time Low's 2012 album *Don't Panic* satirizes various cataclysmic events associated with the phenomenon.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] The phenomenon was also satirized in Brian M.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] A number of brands ran commercials tied to the phenomenon in the days and months leading to the date.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] In February 2012, American automotive company General Motors aired an advertisement during the annual Super Bowl football game in which a group of friends drove Chevrolet Silverados through the ruins of human civilization following the 2012 apocalypse.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] On 17 December 2012, Jell-O ran an ad saying that offering Jell-O to the Mayan gods would appease them into sparing the world.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/2012-phenomenon] John Verret, Professor of Advertising at Boston University, questioned the utility of tying large sums of money to such a unique and short-term event.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Insects are the most numerous and widespread class in the animal kingdom, accounting for up to 90% of all animal species.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] In the 2010s, reports emerged about the widespread decline in populations across multiple insect orders.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The reported severity shocked many observers, even though there had been earlier findings of pollinator decline.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] There have also been anecdotal reports of greater insect abundance earlier in the 20th century.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Many car drivers know this anecdotal evidence through the windscreen phenomenon, for example.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Causes for the decline in insect population are similar to those driving other biodiversity loss.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] They include habitat destruction, such as intensive agriculture, the use of pesticides (particularly insecticides), introduced species, and the effects of climate change.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] An additional cause that may be specific to insects is light pollution (research in that area is ongoing).
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Most commonly, the declines involve reductions in abundance, though in some cases entire species are going extinct.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] In some localities, there have been reports of increases in overall insect population, and some types of insects appear to be increasing in abundance across the world.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Not all insect orders are affected in the same way; most affected are bees, butterflies, moths, beetles, dragonflies and damselflies.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Many of the remaining insect groups have received less research to date.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Also, comparative figures from earlier decades are often not available.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] In the few major global studies, estimates of the total number of insect species at risk of extinction range between 10% and 40%, though all of these estimates have been fraught with controversy.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Studies concur that in areas where insects are declining, their abundance has been diminishing for decades.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Yet, those trends had not been spotted earlier, as there has historically been much less interest in studying insects in comparison to mammals, birds and other vertebrates.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] One reason is the comparative lack of charismatic species of insects.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] In 2016, it was observed that while 30,000 insect species are known to inhabit Central Europe, there are practically no specialists in the region devoted to full-time monitoring.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] This issue of insufficient research is even more acute in the developing countries.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] As of 2021, nearly all of the studies on regional insect population trends come from Europe and the United States, even though they account for less than 20% of insect species worldwide.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] In Africa, Asia and South America there are hardly any observations of insects that span several decades.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Such studies would be required to draw conclusions about population trends on a large scale.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] To respond to these declines, various governments have introduced conservation measures to help insects.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] For example, the German government started an *Action Programme for Insect Protection* in 2018.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The goals of this program include promoting insect habitats in the agricultural landscape, and reducing pesticide use, light pollution, and pollutants in soil and water.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The fossil record concerning insects stretches back hundreds of millions of years.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] It suggests there are ongoing background levels of both new species appearing and extinctions.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Very occasionally, the record also appears to show mass extinctions of insects, understood to be caused by natural phenomena such as volcanic activity or meteor impact.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The Permian–Triassic extinction event saw the greatest level of insect extinction, and the Cretaceous–Paleogene the second highest.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Insect diversity has recovered after mass extinctions, as a result of periods in which new species originate with increased frequency, although the recovery can take millions of years.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Concern about a human-caused Holocene extinction has been growing since the late 20th century, although much of the early concern was not focused on insects.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] In a report on the world's invertebrates, the Zoological Society of London suggested in 2012 that insect populations were in decline globally, affecting pollination and food supplies for other animals.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] It estimated that about 20 percent of all invertebrate species were threatened with extinction, and that species with the least mobility and smallest ranges were most at risk.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Studies finding insect decline have been available for decades—one study tracked a decline from 1840 to 2013—but it was the 2017 re-publication of the German nature reserves study that saw the issue receive widespread attention in the media.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The press reported the decline with alarming headlines, including "Insect Apocalypse".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The insects studied have mostly been butterflies and moths, bees, beetles, dragonflies, damselflies and stoneflies.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Every species is affected in different ways by changes in the environment, and it cannot be inferred that there is a consistent decrease across different insect groups.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] When conditions change, some species adapt easily to the change while others struggle to survive.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] A March 2019 statement by the Entomological Society of America said there was not yet sufficient data to predict an imminent mass extinction of insects and that some of the extrapolated predictions might "have been extended well past the limits of the data or have been otherwise over-hyped".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] For some insect groups such as some butterflies, moths, bees, and beetles, declines in abundance and diversity have been documented in European studies.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] These have generally led to an overall pattern of decline, but there are variable trends for individual species within groups.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] For instance, a minority of British moths are becoming more common.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Other areas have shown increases in some insect species, although trends in most regions are currently unknown.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] It is difficult to assess long-term trends in insect abundance or diversity because historical measurements are generally not known for many species.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Robust data to assess at-risk areas or species is especially lacking for arctic and tropical regions and a majority of the southern hemisphere.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Thomas and other scientists wrote in response to the apocalyptic "Insectageddon" predictions of Sánchez-Bayo, "we respectfully suggest that accounts of the demise of insects may be slightly exaggerated".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] They called for "joined-up thinking" in responding to insect declines, backed up by more robust data than was currently available.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] A 2020 meta-analysis found that globally terrestrial insects appear to be declining in abundance at a rate of about 9% per decade, while the abundance of freshwater insects appears to be increasing by 11% per decade.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The study analysed 166 long-term studies, involving 1676 different sites across the world.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] It found considerable variations in insect decline depending on locality – the authors considered this a hopeful sign, as it suggests local factors, including conservation efforts, can make a big difference.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The article stated that the increase in freshwater insects may in part be due to efforts to clean up lakes and rivers, and may also relate to global warming and enhanced primary productivity driven by increased nutrient inputs.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] However, the data selection and methodology of the article were criticised in several publications and the article now has an editorial expression of concern.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] In 2022, 66 researchers conducted a survey of 3331 biodiversity experts (meaning scientists who published a study on the subject of biodiversity over the past decade).
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] This included 629 experts in terrestrial and freshwater invertebrates: on average, they believed that around 30% (with an uncertainty range between 20 and 50%) of these species are or have been threatened with extinction (including the species which had already gone extinct since 1500).
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] As insects account for the vast majority of the world's invertebrates, this figure by extension applies to them as well.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] A 2019 survey of 24 entomologists working on six continents found that on a scale of 0 to 10, with 10 being the worst, all the scientists rated the severity of the insect decline crisis as being between 8–10.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The Intergovernmental Science-Policy Platform on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services reported its assessment of global biodiversity in 2019.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Its summary for insect life was that "Global trends in insect populations are not known but rapid declines have been well documented in some places. ...
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Local declines of insect populations such as wild bees and butterflies have often been reported, and insect abundance has declined very rapidly in some places even without large-scale land-use change, but the global extent of such declines is not known. ...
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] They argued that more investigations into insects and other "hyperdiverse and understudied taxa" are urgently required to clarify the matter.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The causes of the declines in insect populations, and their relative importance, are not fully understood.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] They are likely to vary between different insect groups and geographical regions.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Other factors that are thought to be important are anthropogenic noise, introduced species, and eutrophication from fertilisers.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The use of increased quantities of insecticides and herbicides on crops have affected not only non-target insect species, but also the plants on which they feed.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Climate change and the introduction of exotic species (see climate change and invasive species) that compete with the indigenous ones put the native species under stress, and as a result they are more likely to succumb to pathogens and parasites.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Plants grow faster in presence of increased CO2 (due to the CO2 fertilisation effect) but the resulting plant biomass contains fewer nutrients.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] While some species such as flies and cockroaches might increase as a result, the total biomass of insects is estimated to be decreasing by between about 0.9 to 2.5% per year.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Insects account for the vast majority of invertebrate species.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The strongest effects were seen in the southern regions, where rapid increases in frequency of extreme warm years had exceeded the species' historical temperature ranges.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] In 2024, a major review paper projected likely extinctions of 14% to 27% insects under RCP4.5 by the year 2070, and 23% to 31% under RCP8.5.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Most of the individual studies tracking insect declines report just abundance, others just on biomass, some on both, and yet others report on all three metrics.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Data directly related to diversity loss at global level is more sparse than for abundance or biomass declines.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Estimates for diversity loss at a planetary level tend to involve extrapolating from abundance or biomass data; while studies sometimes show local extirpation of an insect species, actual world wide extinctions are challenging to discern.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] In a 2019 review, David Wagner noted that currently the Holocene extinction is seeing animal species loss at about 100–1,000 times the planet's normal background rate, and that various studies found a similar, or possibly even faster extinction rate for insects.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Wagner opines that serious though this biodiversity loss is, it is the decline in abundance that will have the most serious ecological impact.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] In theory it is possible for the three metrics to be independent.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] For instance, a decline in biomass might not involve a decrease in abundance or diversity if all that was happening was that typical insects were getting smaller.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] In practice though, abundance and biomass tend to be closely related, typically showing a similar level of decline.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Change in biodiversity is often, though not always, directly proportional to the other two metrics.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Some studies find cases where, in certain locations, change in biodiversity is inversely proportional to the other metrics.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The Rothamsted Insect Survey at Rothamsted Research, Harpenden, England, began monitoring insect suction traps across the UK in 1964.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] According to the group, these have produced "the most comprehensive standardised long-term data on insects in the world".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The traps are "effectively upside-down Hoovers running 24/7, continually sampling the air for migrating insects", according to James Bell, the survey leader, in an interview in 2017 with the journal *Science*.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Between 1970 and 2002, the insect biomass caught in the traps declined by over two-thirds in southern Scotland, although it remained stable in England.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The scientists speculate that insect abundance was already lost in England by 1970 (figures in Scotland were higher than in England when the survey began), or that aphids and other pests increased there in the absence of their insect predators.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] A 2014 review noted: "Of all insects with IUCN-documented population trends [203 insect species in five orders], 33% are declining, with strong variation among orders." In the UK, "30 to 60% of species per order have declining ranges".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Insect pollinators, "needed for 75% of all the world's food crops", appear to be "strongly declining globally in both abundance and diversity", which has been linked in Northern Europe to the decline of plant species that rely on them.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The study referred to the human-caused loss of vertebrates and invertebrates as the "Anthropocene defaunation".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Anecdotal evidence for insect decline has been offered by those who recall apparently greater insect abundance in the 20th century.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Entomologist Simon Leather recalls that, in the 1970s, windows of Yorkshire houses he visited on his early-morning paper round would be "plastered with tiger moths" attracted by the house's lighting during the night.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Tiger moths have now largely disappeared from the area.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Another anecdote is recalled by environmentalist Michael McCarthy concerning the vanishing of the "moth snowstorms", a relatively common sight in the UK in the 1970s and earlier.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Moth snowstorms occurred when moths congregated with such density that they could appear like a blizzard in the beam of automobile headlights.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] In 2004 the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds organised a Big Bug Count, issuing "splatometers" to about 40,000 volunteers to help count the number of insects colliding with their number plates.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] They found an average of one insect per 5 miles (8 km), which was less than expected.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] In 2013 the Krefeld Entomological Society reported a "huge reduction in the biomass of insects" caught in malaise traps in 63 nature reserves in Germany (57 in Nordrhein-Westfalen, one in Rheinland-Pfalz and one in Brandenburg).
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] A reanalysis published in 2017 suggested that, in 1989–2016, there had been a "seasonal decline of 76%, and mid-summer decline of 82%, in flying insect biomass over the 27 years of study".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The decline was "apparent regardless of habitat type" and could not be explained by "changes in weather, land use, and habitat characteristics".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The authors suggested that not only butterflies, moths and wild bees appear to be in decline, as previous studies indicated, but "the flying insect community as a whole".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Scientists stated in 2019: "In 2017, a 27-year long population monitoring study revealed a shocking 76% decline in flying insect biomass at several of Germany's protected areas (Hallmann et al., 2017).
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] This represents an average 2.8% loss in insect biomass per year in habitats subject to rather low levels of human disturbance, which could either be undetectable or regarded statistically non-significant if measurements were carried out over shorter time frames.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] According to *The Economist*, the study was the "third most frequently cited scientific study (of all kinds) in the media in 2017".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The Krefeld study's authors were not able to link the decline to climate change or pesticides, he wrote, but they suggested that intensive farming was involved.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] While agreeing with their conclusions, he cautioned that "the data are based on biomass, not species, and the sites were not sampled continuously and are not globally representative".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] A 2018 study of the El Yunque National Forest in Puerto Rico reported a decline in arthropods, and in lizards, frogs, and birds (insect-eating species) based on measurements in 1976 and 2012.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The American entomologist David Wagner called the study a "clarion call" and "one of the most disturbing articles" he had ever read.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The researchers reported "biomass losses between 98% and 78% for ground-foraging and canopy-dwelling arthropods over a 36-year period, with respective annual losses between 2.7% and 2.2%".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The decline was attributed to a rise in the average temperature; tropical insect species cannot tolerate a wide range of temperatures.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The researchers were shocked by the results: "We couldn't believe the first results.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] I remember [in the 1970s] butterflies everywhere after rain.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] In 2019 a study of butterfly numbers in the Netherlands from 1890 to 2017 reported an estimated decline of 84 percent.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] When analysed by type of habitat, the trend was found to have stabilised in grassland and woodland in recent decades but the decline continued in heathland.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The decline was attributed to changes in land use due to more efficient farming methods, which has caused a decline in weeds.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The recent up-tick in some populations documented in the study was attributed to (conservationist) changes in land management and thus an increase in suitable habitat.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] A 2019 review analysed 73 long-term insect surveys that had shown decline, most of them in the United States and Western Europe.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] While noting population increases for certain species of insects in particular areas, the authors reported an annual 2.5% loss of biomass.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] They wrote that the review "revealed dramatic rates of decline that may lead to the extinction of 40% of the world's insect species over the next few decades", a conclusion that was challenged.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The methodology and strong language of the review were questioned.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Other criticism included that the authors attributed the decline to particular threats based on the studies they reviewed, even when those studies had simply suggested threats rather than clearly identifying them.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Some reviewers said the study might underestimate the rate of insect decline in the tropics.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Some reviewers also had concerns about the review's search terms, geographic biases, calculations of extinction rates, and inaccurate assessment of drivers of population change.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] In a 2020 paper that studied insects and other arthropods across all Long-term Ecological Research (LTER) sites in the U.S., the authors found some declines, some increases, but generally few consistent losses in arthropod abundance or diversity.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] This study found some variation in location, but generally stable numbers of insects.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] As noted in the paper, the authors did not do any *a priori* selection of arthropod taxa.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Instead, they tested the hypothesis that if the arthropod decline was pervasive, it would be detected in monitoring programs not originally designed to look for declines.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] They suggest that overall numbers of insects vary but overall show no net change.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] However, the methodology of the article was criticised because it failed to account for changes in sampling location and sampling effort at LTER sites and for the impact of experimental conditions, had inconsistencies in the database constitution and relied on an inadequate statistical analysis.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The windshield phenomenon – car windscreens covered in dead insects after even a short drive through a rural area in Europe and North America – seems also largely to have disappeared; in the 21st century, drivers find they can go an entire summer without noticing it.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] John Rawlins, head of invertebrate zoology at the Carnegie Museum of Natural History, speculated in 2006 that more aerodynamic car designs could explain the change.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Entomologist Martin Sorg told *Science* in 2017: "I drive a Land Rover, with the aerodynamics of a refrigerator, and these days it stays clean." Rawlins added that land next to high-speed highways has become more manicured and therefore less attractive to insects.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Insect population decline affects ecosystems, and other animal populations, including humans.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Insects are at "the structural and functional base of many of the world's ecosystems." A 2019 global review warned that, if not mitigated by decisive action, the decline would have a catastrophic impact on the planet's ecosystems.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Birds and larger mammals that eat insects can be directly affected by the decline.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Declining insect populations can reduce the ecosystem services provided by beneficial bugs, such as pollination of agricultural crops, and biological waste disposal.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] According to the Zoological Society of London, in addition to such loss of instrumental value, the decline also represents a loss of the declining species' intrinsic value.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The most influential factors, that can be counteracted, are habitat loss and degradation, pesticide use, and climate change.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Policies at all levels of government across the globe are required to address these in a meaningful way.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Much of the world's efforts to retain biodiversity at national level is reported to the United Nations as part of the Convention on Biological Diversity.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Reports typically describe policies to prevent the loss of diversity generally, such as habitat preservation, rather than specifying measures to protect particular taxa.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Pollinators are the main exception to this, with several countries reporting efforts to reduce the decline of their pollinating insects.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Following the 2017 Krefeld and other studies, Germany's environment ministry, the BMU, started an *Action Programme for Insect Protection* (*Aktionsprogramm Insektenschutz*).
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Their goals include promoting insect habitats in the agricultural landscape, and reducing pesticide use, light pollution, and pollutants in soil and water.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Beyond halting habitat loss and fragmentation and limiting climate change, reducing pesticide use is required for preserving insect populations.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Pesticides have been found far from their application source and legislatively mandated elimination of cosmetic pesticide use, as well as general reductions of pesticide use, could greatly benefit insects.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Organic food/farming-related measures can be solutions.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] However, some scientists warned that excessive focus on reducing pesticide use could be counterproductive as pests already cause a 35 percent yield loss in crops, which can rise to 70 percent if pesticides are not used.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] If the yield loss was compensated for by expanding agricultural land with deforestation and other habitat destruction, it could exacerbate insect decline.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Buffer zones around nature reserves where pesticide use is drastically reduced has been proposed for inclusion in the countermeasures.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Scientists who proposed the measure conducted a Germany-wide field study and found that insect samples in these areas are contaminated with ~16 pesticides on average, proportionate to the agricultural production area in a radius of 2 km.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The Entomological Society of America suggests that people maintain plant diversity in their gardens and leave "natural habitat, like leaf litter and dead wood".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The Xerces Society in the U.S. has been doing a Western Monarch Thanksgiving Count which includes observations from volunteers for 22 years.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] It has been suggested that "Because many insects need little space to survive, even partial conversion of lawns to minimally disturbed natural vegetation—say 10%—could significantly aid insect conservation, while simultaneously lowering the cost of lawn maintenance".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] In the UK, 27 British entomologists and ecologists signed an open letter to *The Guardian* in March 2019, calling on the British research establishment to investigate the decline.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The letter requested action "to enable intensive investigation of the real threat of ecological disruption caused by insect declines without delay".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] In a 2019 paper, scientists listed 100 studies and other references suggesting that insects can help meet the Sustainable Development Goals (SDG) adopted in 2015 by the United Nations.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The public in many countries is largely unaware of benefits and services that insects provide (such as honey, ecosystem balance, food for other animals, pollination, soil health, etc.), and negative perceptions of insects are widespread.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] In April 2019, in response to the studies about insect decline, Carol Ann Duffy released several poems, by herself and others, to mark the end of her tenure as Britain's poet laureate and to coincide with protests that month by the environmentalist movement Extinction Rebellion.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] The poets included Fiona Benson, Imtiaz Dharker, Matthew Hollis, Michael Longley, Daljit Nagra, Alice Oswald, and Denise Riley.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Duffy's contribution was "The Human Bee".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] One reason that studies into the decline are limited is that entomology and taxonomy are themselves in decline.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] At the 2019 Entomology Congress, leading entomologist Jürgen Gross said that "We are ourselves an endangered species" while Wolfgang Wägele – an expert in systematic zoology – said that "in the universities we have lost nearly all experts".
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] In 2016, Jürgen Deckert of Berlin Natural History Museum commented that while around 30,000 insect species are known to inhabit Central Europe, there are "only a few specialists" dedicated to the region, and even they often do monitoring as a side job.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] General biology courses in college give less attention to insects, and the number of biologists specialising in entomology is decreasing as specialities such as genetics expand.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] In addition, studies investigating the decline tend to be done by collecting insects and killing them in traps, which poses an ethical problem for conservationists.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Further, the above describes the situation in the developed countries: the developing countries have typically not had time to build up their entomology in the first place.
[src:decline-in-insect-populations/decline-in-insect-populations] Consequently, nearly all of the major insect studies to date are from Europe and the United States, even though it's estimated that fewer than 20% of insect species worldwide are in those countries.
